\series bold
future economic benefits
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A liability is usually considered when there is >50% probable future payables
 (to be more conservative).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Current (in the next 12 months) and non-current assets and liabilities are
 separated.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Example: a car bought with a loan is an asset (both above conditions are
 true).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An alternative way to think of equity: if all assets are sold, and liabilities
 are settled - what is left (belongs to owners / shareholders) is the equity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assets appear in the order of liquidity - thus cash is the first asset to
 appeaar.
\end_layout

